M6A2 5.56mm 16.1 Inch Barrel Black VLTOR EMod Stock MagPul Pistol Grip Black Finish Troy Sights 30 Rounds
The M6A2™ rifle is a standard carbine available in various barrel lengths and in either 5.56mm NATO or 6.8mm SPC. The M6A2 rifle is ideal for those who utilize optical sights as it employs a low-profile gas block. There is no A-frame front sight to obscure the field of view of the optical device. The M6A2 rifle also features a longer midlength free float rail system with a removable return-to-zero top. Any M4 MIL Std 1913 accessory can be mounted to the rail, and because the rail has a monolithic profile, you can bridge devices from the receiver to the rail seamlessly. The longer rail also affords more 1913 “real estate” to mount your accessories.

The M6A2 rifle can be used in various roles. With the 10.5 inch barrel, it is ideal for close quarters battle or fighting in built up areas. The 14.7 inch barrel M6A2 rifle is an excellent general purpose carbine capable of effective fire out to 600 meters. And with the 16.1 inch barrel, the M6A2 rifle can be used as a Squad Dedicated Marksman Rifle.

The M6A2 rifle’s edge in capability, reliability, accuracy and long service life is the result of advanced technology materials and manufacturing processes, combined with progressive patented designs. All LWRCI™ carbine systems feature our short-stroke gas-piston operating system. The operating system is lightweight, self-regulating, and self-scraping. This system of operation does not foul the moving parts of the weapon with carbon or heat which greatly enhances service life and reliability while decreasing both user and armorer maintenance. All M6A2 rifles feature a match grade, cold rotary hammer forged barrel with a target crown. The barrel is treated with NiCorr™ surface conversion technology that extends service life, enhances accuracy, and increases the effective range of the weapon. The action of the M6A2 rifle is coated in our proprietary nickel coating that provides a hard permanent lubrication to the moving parts.

The M6A2 rifle defines itself as the most modern and incrementally evolved carbine in the world. At the same time it also presents the best value. Service life is extended to four times that of a legacy M4, accuracy is 100 percent better, and our M6 rifles are many times more reliable than the legacy gas-impingement design.

title: For Sale:  Hi-Standard Model B!!! Rare!!!
postcontent:
You have the opportunity to own a piece of history. The Hi-Standard model B was the first produced of it's type by Hi-Standard. The Serial number dates it to 1937. It is still in excellent firing condition!!!! Many similar ones have sold for much more. 

When Hi Standard first started producing pistols, the first model they came out with was the model B. They made it in both a long barrel and a short barrel version. The one pictured is the long barrel model. The basic design was derived from an earlier Browning design, as was the Colt Woodsman. In fact, the Woodsman and the Model B look almost identical, although they are not.

The model B turned out to be a reliable, well made, and accurate pistol. Some people didn't like the grip, as for a person with large hands, it was on the short side. On later models this was changed, and the grip was extended. On later models the magazine capacity was increased from nine to ten rounds. Later models also incorporated a slide lock back lever, which the Model B did not have.

I am asking $400 and am open to offers. Feel free to email with any questions.

title: For Sale:  #s matching, 1936 Tula arsenal Mosin Nagant model 91/30 7.62x54r. CN sniper designation.
postcontent:
Camdenton/Linn Creek

FS: Numbers matching, 1936 Tula arsenal Mosin Nagant model 91/30 7.62x54r. CN stamp designation. The marking literally translates to " Snayperskaya Provernnaya" meaning tested for use as a sniper. A Soviet document indicates that 54,160 rifles were produced in the PE form between 1932 and 1938. However only 12,752 top mount hex and round receiver PE/PEM’s were made in 1936. Figure it as a 50/50 split and that leaves 6,376 hex receivers. Of that number, how many 
A) survived the war, 
B) survived bubba's tender touch 
C) how many were left 'un converted~drilled/tapped for a scope and mount. 
and D) in better than average condition. 

My guess, not too very many at all. I hate the 'R' word but can call this one pretty damned uncommon & feel comfortable with that. I believe these unconverted models to be even less common than full drilled/tapped models.

This ol'vet is wearing a post war stock with an arsenal repaired toe splice. The shellac is flaking in a few places, not horribly so, but it's still there. It doesn't bother me so I haven't done anything to it. 95% blue/black remains on the metal. Clean muzzle crown, deep & strong rifling. Silky smooth action. Point of aim & damned accurate. 

$300 firm. If it doesn't sell I'm happy to keep this one in my collection.

Pick up in Linn Creek. I am willing to ship on your dime with you paying ffl fees on both sides. (19 photos upon request)

title: For Sale:  Ballistic Advantage 16" mid-length ar-15 rifle barrel
postcontent:
This listing is for a new, unfired barrel made for Special Ops Tactical by Ballistic Advantage, LLC. This barrel is 16" long and is chambered in 5.56x45mm NATO.  In my opinion the features of this barrel make it among the finest all-purpose barrels for the AR platform at any price point.

First this barrel features a unique profile making for the best blend of accuracy and weight available.  The common military profile is thinnest under the handguard and heavy at the muzzle which makes for a barrel that both gets hot and introduces "barrel whip" which degrades accuracy.  This barrel is built for just the opposite.  Its a full ounce lighter than a 16" government barrel (27oz vs 28oz) and feels much more balanced without the extra weight out at the muzzle.  Yet it is much more rigid and accurate!

Also this barrel also has a QPQ Nitride finish both down the bore and outside.  This treatment which surface-hardens the barrel steel and greatly extends the life of the rifling and chamber throat.  It works so well that barrels treated with it are said to last 30% longer than hard chrome-lined barrels and are many times more resistant to corrosion.  Also unlike hard chrome plating, QPQ Nitride is a treatment and doesn't affect the tolerances in the bore and chamber leaving accuracy intact.  The process is also responsible for the attractive and scratch resistant flat finish on the outside of the barrel.  Its very similar to the process used on Glock slides and leads to a similar appearance.

The QPQ treatment is sometimes used on cheap barrels to make them seem desirable but to do it correctly the barrels must be treated before the barrel extension is added or the extensions can loosen during the heating of the process and lead to inaccuracy or failures.  Many manufacturers skip this step but that clearly is not the case on this barrel as it features a Fail-Zero nickel boron coated barrel extension.  This extremely slick coating has 3 advantages on a barrel extension.  It prevents the barrel from seizing in the receiver for easy installation and removal, provides the most reliable feeding via the feed ramps, and makes for a smoother working interaction with the bolt for less wear and action failures.

You can see this was a well-thought out barrel with a lot of features that set it apart.  Here's a full list of features:

    5.56x45mm NATO chamber also suitable for .223 Remington ammunition
    1/7 twist rate will stabilize virtually any available ammunition
    Mid length gas system is ideal for 16" barrels
    Accepts common .750" gas blocks
    Standard 1/2x28 threads for muzzle device
    4150 chrome moly vanadium steel alloy construction
    High pressure tested and magnetic particle inspected
    Unique barrel profile leads to enhanced accuracy and balance
    QPQ Nitride treatment for enhanced barrel life
    Fail-Zero nib coating for enhanced feeding and reliability


Please feel free to ask questions about this barrel.  Its an excellent cornerstone to a new or upgraded AR upper suitable for combat, competition, varmint hunting, and target shooting.

title: For Sale:   Winchester 1892 ANTIQUE Take Down in .38 WCF with Close Coupled Double Set Triggers
postcontent:
This is a very nice Model 1892 Winchester take-down rifle with octagon barrel, Lyman No. 2 Combination tang peep sight and close coupled double set triggers, manufactured in 1895 (serial #119xxx). The mechanics are perfect and the bore is good with strong rifling but shows some frosting and shallow pitting, though still shiny. The deluxe wood is in good condition with much of the original varnish finish. The receiver is mostly bare with some blue in protected areas. The barrel retains 50%original blue, starting to patina, and the magazine tube is 50% as well. The rifle qualifies as an antique since it was made in 1895, but was actually not shipped form the factory until October 30, 1899. 

What make this gun unique are the close coupled double set triggers which are extremely rare on models 1892 and 1894. These triggers and the tang sight were probably added after the gun left the factory, as they are not mentioned in factory records as being shipped with the gun originally. The original special features when the gun was shipped are the take-down feature and deluxe wood.
